MgII2796:

Drullinger et al. (1980) give:
dnu(26,24) = 3050 MHz = 0.101737 cm-1.
dnu(25,24) = 1589 MHz = 0.053003 cm-1.

According the Pickering et al. (1998), there are two main groups of 25
lines, split by hyperfine structure. The first group lies
dnu(26,25)=772.1 MHz = 0.025754 cm-1 below the frequency of the 26
component; that is
dnu(25[F=3?],24)=2277.9 MHz = 0.075983 cm-1.
Thus, if the centre of gravity is to lie on the predicted position of
the isotopic shift then we have:
dnu(25[F=2?],24)=(0.053003 - 7/12*0.075983)/(5/12)
                =0.020831 cm-1.
So,
x(24)=35760.851 - 0.042*0.020831 - 0.058*0.075983 - 0.11*0.101737
     =35760.834527
x(25[F=2?])=35760.855358
x(25[F=3?])=35760.910510
x(26)=35760.936264


MgII2803:

The calculations of Berengut et al. (2003) show almost identical
k_NMS, k_SMS and F values for MgII2796 and MgII2803. Therefore, I'm
going to use exactly the same dnu(26,24) and dnu(25,24) values for
MgII2803 as for MgII2796. According to Pickering et al. (1998), the
splitting within each of the two main groups of 25 isotopic components
is 5 times larger in this transition compared to MgII2796. Even still,
the splitting is still very small and I ignore it here. Thus:

dnu(26,24) = 3050 MHz = 0.101737 cm-1.
dnu(25,24) = 1589 MHz = 0.053003 cm-1.
dnu(25[F=3?],24)=2277.9 MHz = 0.075983 cm-1.
dnu(25[F=2?],24)=0.020831 cm-1.

So,
x(24)=35669.303 - 0.042*0.020831 - 0.058*0.075983 - 0.11*0.101737
     =35669.286527
x(25[F=2?])=35669.307358
x(25[F=3?])=35669.362510
x(26)=35669.388264



