ZnII2026:

Matsubara et al. (2003) have measured the isotopic shifts of the 66,
68 and 70 isotopes from the 64 one. They estimate the 67 shift but the
hyperfine splitting of the ground state is much larger than the
isotopic shift. They ignore the supposedly much smaller hyperfine
splitting of the excited state. The values are:

dnu(64,66) =  676(6) MHz = 0.022549 cm-1.
dnu(64,68) = 1346(7) MHz = 0.044898 cm-1.
dnu(64,70) = 1914(12) MHz = 0.063844 cm-1.
dnu(64,67[F=2]) = 4100 MHz = 0.136761 cm-1.
dnu(64,67[F=3]) = -3100 MHz = -0.103405 cm-1.

For X = 49355.005,
x(64) = 49355.005 - 0.2790*0.022549 - 0.0410*5/12*0.136761 - 0.0410*7/12*(-0.103405) - 0.1875*0.044898 - 0.0062*0.063844
     =49354.990031
x(66)=49355.012580
x(67[F=2])=49355.126792
x(67[F=3])=49354.886626
x(68)=49355.034929
x(70)=49355.053875


ZnII2062:

The calculations of Berengut et al. (2003) show that the contributions
to the ZnII2062 isotopic shifts are very similar to those of the
ZnII2026 transition. The ratio of the total shifts is 2062:2026 =
653/632 = 1.033228. Therefore, it seems sensible to apply this scaling
to the measured shifts of Matsubara et al. for the 2026 in order to
get the likely shifts for the ZnII2062 line.

dnu(64,66) =  698.5 MHz = 0.023298 cm-1.
dnu(64,68) = 1390.7 MHz = 0.046390 cm-1.
dnu(64,70) = 1977.6 MHz = 0.065966 cm-1.
dnu(64,67[F=2]) = 4236.2 MHz = 0.141306 cm-1.
dnu(64,67[F=3]) = -3203.0 MHz = -0.106841 cm-1.

For X = 48481.081,
x(64) = 48481.081 - 0.2790*0.023298 - 0.0410*5/12*0.141306 - 0.0410*7/12*(-0.106841) - 0.1875*0.046390 - 0.0062*0.065966
     =48481.065534
x(66)=48481.088832
x(67[F=2])=48481.206840
x(67[F=3])=48480.958693
x(68)=48481.111924
x(70)=48481.131500


